## What Each Section Tests and Why

| Section | What It Covers | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| **1 – Accepted File Types** | PDF / PNG / JPG / JPEG pass; 10 other types fail; MIME ≠ extension rejected | Directly enforces the format whitelist |
| **2 – File Size Constraints** | Exact 10 MB boundary, 1-byte over, empty, parametric sizes | Validates the boundary condition precisely |
| **3 – Error Response Details** | Messages reference the offending type/size | Supports developer and user diagnostics |
| **4 – Successful Upload Response** | `success`, `document_id`, `url`, `employee_id` all present | Confirms the contract for callers |
| **5 – Webhook Happy Path** | Called once, correct event name, all payload fields present | Core webhook requirement |
| **6 – Webhook Not Emitted on Rejection** | No webhook for invalid files; storage also untouched | Prevents false notifications |
| **7 – Webhook Failure Handling** | Upload still succeeds; failure is logged | Resilience: external consumer outage must not block employee |
| **8 – Missing / Invalid Input** | `None` employee ID, empty filename, missing file | Defensive input validation |
| **9 – Storage Failure** | Webhook not fired if file was never stored | Consistency: don't notify about a non-existent document |
| **10 – Multiple Uploads** | Two uploads → two events; correct employee IDs per event | Correctness under realistic workload |

